@dubeejw - I was able to recreate this failure with the following action.  The CLI is apparently not handling the error parsing well when the error response is an object.  The HTTP response successfully returns the error object, but the CLI has a parsing bug that results in the error `error: Unable to invoke action 'whiskrejectobj': The connection failed, or timed out. (HTTP status code 502)`

whiskrejrectobj.js

```
function main(message) {
    return Promise.reject({
        name: 'myname',
        aflag: true,
        reason: 'failure cause'
    });
}
```

Then run `wsk action invoke whiskrejectobj -b -v`

@rabbah, the issue from the CLI perspective is that it is not expecting an error object containing and error string. Instead the CLI is looking for the error string in the response object.

Here's the response from an async promise that fails:

```
"response": {
        "status": "application error",
        "statusCode": 0,
        "success": false,
        "result": {
            "error": {
                "error": "The requested resource does not exist. (undefined)"
            }
        }
    }
```

Note the dual error fields.

```
> cat t.js 
function main(params) {
   return Promise.reject({error: 'failed activation'});
}
> wsk action update t.js t.js
> wsk action invoke t.js --blocking
error: Unable to invoke action 't.js': The connection failed, or timed out. (HTTP status code 502)
```

i think this fix is also not correct - i rebased this pr and for the example above:

```
the response is what's expected:

